# Unified Trading System UI — Cursor Rules

These rules ensure architectural coherence, maintainability, and consistency across the UI codebase.

**Read before any implementation work.**

---

## ⚠️ CURRENT STATE vs TARGET STATE

**These rules describe the TARGET architecture.** The codebase is currently in **pre-Phase 2** state:

| What | Current (pre-Phase 2) | Target (these rules) |
|------|----------------------|---------------------|
| App structure | FLAT `app/` with 30+ route dirs | `app/(public)/`, `app/(platform)/`, `app/(ops)/` route groups |
| Mock data | ~9,100 lines inline in `lib/*.ts` | MSW handlers in `lib/mocks/handlers/` with persona-scoped fixtures |
| State management | None | Zustand stores in `lib/stores/` + React Query in `hooks/api/` |
| API layer | None (pages render static data) | React Query hooks in `hooks/api/` consuming MSW or real APIs |
| Auth | Bare `localStorage` read | Demo personas with entitlements, role-based nav/data scoping |
| Config | None | Centralized in `lib/config/` |

**Read `UI_STRUCTURE_MANIFEST.json` for exact current state and what Phase 2 needs to create.**
**Read `REFACTORING_PLAN_PHASE_1-4.md` for the phased migration plan.**

When building new code, follow these rules (target patterns). When touching existing code, migrate it toward these patterns incrementally.

---

## 1. Architecture-First Organization

### Rule 1.1: Structure by Service Domain, Not by Feature

This project uses **Next.js 16 App Router** with file-system routing.

**CORE ARCHITECTURAL PRINCIPLE: One Platform, Filtered.**

Internal users and external clients land on THE SAME PLATFORM. The pages are the same.
The components are the same. What changes is:
- What DATA the API returns (scoped by org + subscription entitlements)
- What NAV ITEMS are visible (filtered by entitlements)
- What FILTER OPTIONS appear in dropdowns (e.g., org selector: internal sees all orgs, client sees only theirs)

There is NOT a separate "client portal" and "internal portal." There is ONE platform with
data-driven scoping. If a client has subscribed to everything, they see nearly the same
thing as internal — minus the ops/admin surfaces.

**DO:**
```
app/
├── (public)/                          ← Route group: unauthenticated marketing pages
│   ├── page.tsx                       ← Landing page (service showcase, pricing)
│   ├── services/[domain]/page.tsx     ← Service detail pages (what they get if they subscribe)
│   ├── contact/page.tsx
│   ├── login/page.tsx
│   ├── signup/page.tsx
│   └── layout.tsx                     ← PublicShell (header, CTA, footer — no sidebar)
│
├── (platform)/                        ← Route group: THE platform (same for internal AND client)
│   ├── overview/page.tsx              ← Service hub (grid, activity feed, quick actions, health bar)
│   ├── service/[key]/page.tsx         ← Per-service subscription page
│   ├── data/page.tsx                  ← Data service dashboard (subscriptions, instruments)
│   ├── trading/                       ← Live Trading Platform (nested routes)
│   │   ├── page.tsx                   ← Trading terminal (order entry, charts)
│   │   ├── positions/page.tsx         ← Positions management
│   │   ├── risk/page.tsx              ← Risk dashboard
│   │   ├── alerts/page.tsx            ← Alert management
│   │   └── markets/page.tsx           ← Market overview
│   ├── research/                      ← Research & Backtesting (nested routes)
│   │   ├── page.tsx                   ← Research hub
│   │   ├── strategy/                  ← Strategy platform (backtests, candidates)
│   │   ├── ml/                        ← ML models, features, experiments
│   │   └── execution/                 ← Execution research (algos, TCA)
│   ├── execution/page.tsx             ← Live execution analytics
│   ├── reports/                       ← Reporting (nested routes)
│   │   ├── page.tsx                   ← Reports hub (P&L, settlement, attribution)
│   │   └── executive/page.tsx         ← Executive dashboard
│   ├── health/page.tsx                ← Service health dashboard
│   └── layout.tsx                     ← PlatformShell (auth required, entitlement-driven nav)
│
├── (ops)/                             ← Route group: internal-only operational surfaces
│   ├── admin/page.tsx                 ← Admin dashboard (user, client, fee management)
│   ├── ops/page.tsx                   ← Service health, job monitoring
│   ├── devops/page.tsx                ← DevOps (6-tab layout, 17K lines from deployment-ui)
│   ├── manage/                        ← Client/mandate/fee management
│   ├── compliance/page.tsx            ← FCA info page
│   ├── config/page.tsx                ← System configuration
│   ├── engagement/page.tsx            ← Internal engagement admin
│   ├── internal/data-etl/page.tsx     ← ETL pipeline management
│   └── layout.tsx                     ← OpsShell (auth + role=internal required)
│
├── layout.tsx                         ← Root layout (fonts, providers, analytics)
└── globals.css                        ← Design system tokens
│
components/                            ← Shared across all route groups
├── ui/                                ← Radix UI primitives (button, card, dialog, etc.)
├── trading/                           ← Domain-specific trading components
├── shell/                             ← Shell infrastructure (unified-shell, lifecycle-nav)
├── dashboards/                        ← Dashboard layouts (trader, quant, risk, etc.)
├── platform/                          ← Platform components (filter-bar, context-bar)
└── marketing/                         ← Public page components
│
lib/                                   ← Utilities, config, types, mocks
├── config/                            ← API config, branding, constants
├── mocks/                             ← MSW handlers + fixtures (target state)
├── stores/                            ← Zustand stores (filter, auth, ui prefs)
├── types/                             ← Shared TypeScript types
├── registry/                          ← OpenAPI specs, config registry, reference data
└── utils.ts                           ← Utility functions (cn, etc.)
│
hooks/                                 ← Custom React hooks (useAuth, useMobile, useToast, api/)
```

**NOTE:** Old flat paths (`/positions`, `/risk`, `/alerts`, `/markets`, `/strategy-platform/*`, `/ml/*`, `/executive`)
redirect to their new nested locations under `/trading/*`, `/research/*`, and `/reports/*` respectively.

**DON'T:**
```
app/
├── execution/
├── executionV2/                       ❌ Two versions of truth
├── client-execution/                  ❌ Separate client version of the same page
├── internal-execution/                ❌ Separate internal version
│
components/
├── DataFilter.tsx                     ❌ Scattered filters
├── ClientDataFilter.tsx               ❌ Client-specific duplicate
```

**Why:** `(public)` is marketing. `(platform)` is THE product — one set of pages serving internal AND client
users with data-driven scoping. `(ops)` is internal-only admin/deployment surfaces that clients never need.
This structure:
- Eliminates the need to build the same page twice for different roles
- Auth + entitlements in layout.tsx control what nav items + data scopes users get
- Same pages, same components, different registries — easier to build and maintain
- File-system routing = no router config to maintain

---

### Rule 1.2: Never Leave Old Code Alongside New

**DO:**
```
When refactoring PositionsTable:
1. Update PositionsTable.tsx in place
2. Update all imports (routes should not change)
3. Delete old implementation when done
4. Commit with message: "refactor: improve PositionsTable layout and performance"
```

**DON'T:**
```
❌ Create PositionsTableV2.tsx
❌ Create PositionsTableRefactored.tsx
❌ Update routes to point to new component
❌ Leave old component in place
→ Result: Two versions in production, confused routing, split traffic
```

**Why:** Multiple versions create:
- Routing ambiguity (which page is the "real" one?)
- Duplicated state management
- Inconsistent user experience
- Maintenance burden (fix both? or just new?)

**Exception:** Only use versioning if:
- Both versions run simultaneously (A/B testing)
- Old version explicitly deprecated and scheduled for removal
- Clear feature flags separate traffic
- Document the deprecation plan in code

---

## 2. Centralized Components & Reuse

### Rule 2.1: Shared Patterns Go to `components/`

**Common patterns that MUST be centralized in `components/`:**

| Pattern | Location | What to centralize |
|---------|----------|-------------------|
| **Filters** | `components/platform/filter-bar.tsx` | Structure, styling, behavior |
| **Tables** | `components/ui/table.tsx` | Sorting, pagination, filtering |
| **Cards** | `components/ui/card.tsx` | Layout, spacing, shadows |
| **Forms** | `components/ui/form.tsx` | Input validation, labels |
| **Modals** | `components/ui/dialog.tsx` | Backdrop, sizing, animations |
| **Badges/Status** | `components/trading/status-badge.tsx` | Color mapping, icons, text |

```typescript
// ✅ components/platform/filter-bar.tsx — one implementation, used everywhere
export const FilterBar: React.FC<FilterBarProps> = ({ filters, onApply, onClear }) => { ... }

// ✅ app/(platform)/execution/positions/page.tsx
import { FilterBar } from '@/components/platform/filter-bar';

export default function PositionsPage() {
  return <FilterBar filters={POSITION_FILTERS} onApply={handleFilter} onClear={handleClear} />
}
```

**DON'T:**
```typescript
// ❌ components/execution-filter.tsx + components/data-filter.tsx + components/research-filter.tsx
// Each implements filters differently = inconsistent UX
```

---

### Rule 2.2: Branding & Theme in One Place

**All brand/theme values go to `globals.css` tokens + `lib/config/branding.ts`:**

```typescript
// ✅ lib/config/branding.ts
export const BRANDING = {
  company: {
    name: "Unified Trading System",
    shortName: "UTS",
    logo: "/images/logo.svg",          // URL, not hardcoded
    favicon: "/images/favicon.ico",
  },
  colors: {
    primary: "#1a1a1a",                // Dark institutional
    accent: "#00d9ff",
    success: "#00cc88",
    warning: "#ffaa00",
    danger: "#ff4444",
    border: "#333333",
  },
  spacing: {
    xs: "4px",
    sm: "8px",
    md: "16px",
    lg: "24px",
    xl: "32px",
  },
  typography: {
    fontFamily: "Inter, system-ui, sans-serif",
    fontSize: {
      xs: "11px",
      sm: "12px",
      md: "14px",
      lg: "16px",
    },
  },
};

export const getColorForStatus = (status: string) => {
  const statusColorMap: Record<string, string> = {
    OPEN: BRANDING.colors.warning,
    FILLED: BRANDING.colors.success,
    CANCELLED: BRANDING.colors.danger,
  };
  return statusColorMap[status] || BRANDING.colors.primary;
};
```

**Usage:**
```typescript
// ✅ Any component
import { BRANDING } from '@/lib/config/branding';

const Header = () => (
  <header style={{ backgroundColor: BRANDING.colors.primary }}>
    <img src={BRANDING.company.logo} alt={BRANDING.company.name} />
  </header>
);
```

**DON'T:**
```typescript
// ❌ Hardcoded in components
const Header = () => (
  <header style={{ backgroundColor: "#1a1a1a" }}>
    <img src="/images/logo.svg" alt="UTS" />
  </header>
);

// ❌ Different values in different places
// services/execution/Header.tsx: "#1a1a1a"
// services/data/Header.tsx: "#1a2a2a"
// → Inconsistent branding
```

**Why:**
- Change brand color? Update one place → all pages update
- Easy to support dark/light themes (swap entire config)
- No scattered magic strings
- A/B testing themes is trivial

---

### Rule 2.3: Same Pages, Different Data — Auth-Driven Scoping

**The platform is ONE system. Internal and client users see the SAME pages.**
What changes is the DATA and FILTER scope, not the UI components.

**How scoping works in practice:**

```typescript
// ✅ hooks/use-auth.ts returns the user's scope
const { role, org, entitlements } = useAuth();

// role: "internal" | "client" | "public"
// org: { id, name } — internal sees all orgs via selector, client sees their org only
// entitlements: ["data-pro", "execution-basic", "ml-full", ...] — or ["*"] for internal
```

**Pattern: Same page, different registries**

```typescript
// ✅ Data catalogue page — SAME component for internal and client
function DataCataloguePage() {
  const { org, entitlements } = useAuth();
  // API returns instruments scoped to org's subscription
  // Internal gets full instrument registry; client gets their subscription subset
  const { data } = useInstrumentRegistry({ org_id: org.id });

  // Internal sees all orgs in the selector; client sees only their org
  // The page, layout, and components are IDENTICAL — only the data differs
  return <InstrumentGrid data={data} />;
}
```

**Pattern: Nav visibility driven by entitlements**

```typescript
// ✅ components/shell/platform-nav.tsx
const { entitlements, role } = useAuth();

const navItems = PLATFORM_SERVICES.filter(service =>
  service.entitlement_required === null ||  // always visible
  entitlements.includes(service.entitlement_required) ||
  entitlements.includes("*")  // internal sees all
);

// Ops nav items (admin, deployment) only visible to internal
const showOpsNav = role === "internal";
```

**Pattern: Org selector scope**

```typescript
// ✅ components/trading/org-client-selector.tsx
const { role, org } = useAuth();

// Internal: show all organisations in dropdown
// Client: show only their organisation (selector hidden or read-only)
const orgs = role === "internal"
  ? useAllOrganisations()
  : [org];  // single org, no selector needed
```

**THREE USP DIFFERENTIATORS to keep in mind when building ANY page:**

1. **Breadth** — We supply access to every part of a trading system for every data source.
   Every page should reflect the full coverage (33 venues, 5 asset classes, 17+ strategy types).

2. **Seamless internal/external** — Internal and client users see the SAME system, filtered.
   Marketing pages show what's available BEFORE login. After login, clients see the same thing
   as internal, filtered by their subscription. Never build a separate "client version."

3. **Backtest ↔ Live diff** — If you use our data, models, and strategies, the analytics platform
   shows the diff between backtested results and live results visually. This is a key selling point
   that should be prominent in the strategy/execution analytics pages.

**DON'T:**
```typescript
// ❌ Build separate client and internal versions of the same page
// components/ClientPositionsTable.tsx + components/InternalPositionsTable.tsx
// → ONE PositionsTable, different data from the API

// ❌ Hardcode role checks deep in components
// if (role === "client") { return <SimplifiedView /> }
// → Let the API handle scoping; the UI renders what it gets
```

**Why:**
- One implementation per page — half the code, consistent UX
- API handles data scoping (org, subscription) — UI just renders
- New subscription tier? Update entitlements config, not UI code
- Easier to demo: switch persona, see different scope instantly

---

## 3. Configuration & Abstraction

### Rule 3.1: No Hardcoded API Endpoints

**DO:**
```typescript
// ✅ lib/config/api.ts
export const API_CONFIG = {
  baseUrl: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL || 'http://localhost:8004',

  services: {
    execution: {
      baseUrl: '/api/execution',
      endpoints: {
        positions: '/positions',
        orders: '/orders',
        executions: '/executions',
      },
    },
    risk: {
      baseUrl: '/api/risk',
      endpoints: {
        limits: '/limits',
        exposure: '/exposure',
        alerts: '/alerts',
      },
    },
    data: {
      baseUrl: '/api/data',
      endpoints: {
        catalog: '/catalog',
        subscribe: '/subscribe',
        quotes: '/quotes',
      },
    },
  },

  timeouts: {
    short: 5000,
    medium: 15000,
    long: 60000,
  },
};

// Build URLs
export const getExecutionUrl = (endpoint: string) =>
  `${API_CONFIG.baseUrl}${API_CONFIG.services.execution.baseUrl}${API_CONFIG.services.execution.endpoints[endpoint]}`;
```

```typescript
// ✅ hooks/api/usePositions.ts
import { API_CONFIG } from '@/lib/config/api';

export const usePositions = () => {
  const url = `${API_CONFIG.baseUrl}${API_CONFIG.services.execution.baseUrl}${API_CONFIG.services.execution.endpoints.positions}`;
  return fetch(url).then(r => r.json());
};
```

**DON'T:**
```typescript
// ❌ Hardcoded everywhere
fetch('http://localhost:8004/api/execution/positions')
fetch('http://localhost:8004/api/execution/orders')
fetch('http://localhost:8004/api/execution/executions')

// Change base URL? Must update 100s of places
// Want to add /v2 to API paths? Global search-and-replace nightmare
```

**Why:**
- Single source of truth for API structure
- Easy to switch between local/staging/prod
- Mock API uses same config (see Rule 3.3)
- CI/CD can inject endpoints without code changes

---

### Rule 3.2: Service-Specific Config in lib/config/

**All config lives in `lib/config/`, organized by service:**

```
lib/
├── config/
│   ├── api.ts                      ← API endpoints
│   ├── branding.ts                 ← Brand/theme
│   ├── auth.ts                     ← Roles, permissions, demo personas
│   ├── services/
│   │   ├── execution.config.ts     ← Execution table columns, statuses
│   │   ├── data.config.ts          ← Data catalogue config
│   │   └── ...
│   └── index.ts                    ← Single export point
```

```typescript
// ✅ lib/config/services/execution.config.ts
export const POSITION_COLUMNS = [
  { key: 'symbol', label: 'Symbol', width: '100px' },
  { key: 'quantity', label: 'Qty', width: '80px', align: 'right' },
  { key: 'entry_price', label: 'Entry', width: '100px', align: 'right' },
  { key: 'current_price', label: 'Current', width: '100px', align: 'right' },
  { key: 'pnl', label: 'P&L', width: '100px', align: 'right' },
];

export const ORDER_STATUSES = {
  OPEN: { label: 'Open', color: 'warning', icon: 'clock' },
  FILLED: { label: 'Filled', color: 'success', icon: 'check' },
  CANCELLED: { label: 'Cancelled', color: 'danger', icon: 'x' },
};
```

```typescript
// ✅ lib/config/index.ts
export { API_CONFIG } from './api';
export { BRANDING } from './branding';
export { AUTH_ROLES, DEMO_PERSONAS } from './auth';
export { POSITION_COLUMNS, ORDER_STATUSES } from './services/execution.config';
```

```typescript
// ✅ Any component
import { POSITION_COLUMNS, ORDER_STATUSES } from '@/lib/config';

const PositionsTable = ({ data }) => {
  return (
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          {POSITION_COLUMNS.map(col => <th key={col.key}>{col.label}</th>)}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {data.map(row => (
          <tr key={row.id}>
            {POSITION_COLUMNS.map(col => <td key={col.key}>{row[col.key]}</td>)}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  );
};
```

**Why:**
- Service-specific config lives near the feature
- But accessed through unified `lib/config`
- Easy to find both global and service-specific settings
- No imports from deep paths like `../../services/execution/config`

---

### Rule 3.3: Centralized Mock API (Not Per-Page)

**MIGRATION STATUS:** We are migrating FROM inline mock data (`lib/*.ts` static objects) TO MSW (Mock Service Worker) handlers. The target structure below is what we're building toward. New mock data MUST use the MSW pattern. Existing inline mocks will be migrated incrementally.

**Mock data must be schema-compliant** — validated against `lib/registry/openapi.json` (our real backend API spec). Don't invent fields; match the contracts.

**Target structure:**

```
lib/mocks/
├── browser.ts                     ← MSW browser worker setup
├── handlers/
│   ├── auth.ts                    ← Auth mock (returns user profile + entitlements by persona)
│   ├── execution.ts               ← Execution service mocks
│   ├── data.ts                    ← Data service mocks
│   ├── risk.ts                    ← Risk service mocks
│   ├── strategy.ts                ← Strategy service mocks
│   └── ...
├── fixtures/
│   ├── personas.ts                ← Demo user personas with role + entitlements
│   ├── positions.json
│   ├── orders.json
│   ├── strategies.json
│   └── ...
└── index.ts
```

**Demo Personas (auth mocking — CRITICAL for demonstrating the USP):**

```typescript
// ✅ lib/mocks/fixtures/personas.ts
export const DEMO_PERSONAS = {
  "internal-trader": {
    user_id: "iggy",
    org_id: "odum-internal",
    role: "internal",
    entitlements: ["*"],  // sees everything — all orgs, all services, all instruments
    display_name: "Iggy (Internal Trader)",
  },
  "client-full": {
    user_id: "sarah-blucoast",
    org_id: "blue-coast-capital",
    role: "client",
    entitlements: ["data-pro", "execution-full", "ml-full", "reporting", "strategy-full"],
    display_name: "Sarah Chen (Blue Coast — Full Suite)",
    // Full subscription: sees nearly the same as internal, minus ops/admin
    // Org selector locked to blue-coast-capital
    // Instrument registry = their subscription set (still large)
  },
  "client-data-only": {
    user_id: "mike-quantedge",
    org_id: "quant-edge-capital",
    role: "client",
    entitlements: ["data-basic"],
    display_name: "Mike Ross (Quant Edge — Data Only)",
    // Limited subscription: sees data catalogue + API keys only
    // No execution, no ML, no strategy — those nav items hidden
    // Instrument registry = basic tier subset
  },
  "prospect": {
    user_id: "demo-visitor",
    org_id: null,
    role: "public",
    entitlements: [],
    display_name: "Demo Visitor",
    // Sees marketing pages only — service descriptions, pricing, signup CTA
  },
} as const;
```

**Dimensional mocking — the API returns different data per persona, not different pages:**

```typescript
// ✅ lib/mocks/handlers/data.ts
import { http, HttpResponse } from 'msw';
import { FULL_INSTRUMENT_REGISTRY, BASIC_INSTRUMENT_REGISTRY } from '../fixtures/instruments';

export const dataHandlers = [
  // Same endpoint, different response based on auth context
  http.get('/api/data/instruments', ({ request }) => {
    const orgId = request.headers.get('X-Org-Id');
    const tier = request.headers.get('X-Subscription-Tier');

    if (tier === 'data-pro' || orgId === 'odum-internal') {
      return HttpResponse.json({ instruments: FULL_INSTRUMENT_REGISTRY, total: 2400 });
    }
    return HttpResponse.json({ instruments: BASIC_INSTRUMENT_REGISTRY, total: 180 });
  }),

  // Download status — same page, scoped to org's instruments
  http.get('/api/data/status', ({ request }) => {
    const orgId = request.headers.get('X-Org-Id');
    // Returns download progress bars for THIS org's entitled instruments
    return HttpResponse.json({ status: getStatusForOrg(orgId) });
  }),
];
```

The key: **same page component, same endpoint URL, different response data.** Switch persona in the UI → see different scope instantly. This IS the demo.

```typescript
// ✅ lib/mocks/browser.ts
import { setupWorker } from 'msw/browser';
import { authHandlers } from './handlers/auth';
import { executionHandlers } from './handlers/execution';
import { dataHandlers } from './handlers/data';
import { riskHandlers } from './handlers/risk';

export const worker = setupWorker(
  ...authHandlers,
  ...executionHandlers,
  ...dataHandlers,
  ...riskHandlers,
);

// Install in app entry when NEXT_PUBLIC_MOCK_API=true
if (process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_MOCK_API === 'true') {
  worker.start({ onUnhandledRequest: 'bypass' });
}
```

```typescript
// ✅ lib/mocks/handlers/execution.ts
import { http, HttpResponse } from 'msw';
import { API_CONFIG } from '@/lib/config/api';
import { POSITIONS_FIXTURE } from '../fixtures/positions.json';

export const executionHandlers = [
  http.get(`${API_CONFIG.baseUrl}/api/execution/positions`, () => {
    return HttpResponse.json({
      data: POSITIONS_FIXTURE,
      timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
    });
  }),

  http.post(`${API_CONFIG.baseUrl}/api/execution/orders`, async ({ request }) => {
    const body = await request.json();
    return HttpResponse.json({
      order_id: `ORD-${Date.now()}`,
      status: 'OPEN',
      ...body,
    });
  }),
];
```

```typescript
// ✅ hooks/api/use-positions.ts
import { useQuery } from '@tanstack/react-query';
import { API_CONFIG } from '@/lib/config/api';

export const usePositions = () => {
  return useQuery({
    queryKey: ['positions'],
    queryFn: async () => {
      const url = `${API_CONFIG.baseUrl}/api/execution/positions`;
      const response = await fetch(url);
      return response.json();
    },
  });
};

// Works with:
// ✅ Real API (production)
// ✅ Real API (staging, with different baseUrl)
// ✅ Mock API (local dev, same endpoint structure)
// ✅ Mock API (testing, with MSW)
```

**DON'T:**
```typescript
// ❌ Mock per component
// components/execution/mocks/usePositionsMock.ts
// components/data/mocks/useDataMock.ts
// → Each implements mocking differently
// → Inconsistent mock behavior
// → Tests pass but prod fails (different code paths)

// ❌ Hardcoded mock data
const MOCK_POSITIONS = [
  { symbol: 'BTC/USD', qty: 1.5, ... },
  { symbol: 'ETH/USD', qty: 10, ... },
];
// → Changes to mock data scattered
// → Easy to forget to update all places
```

**Why:**
- One mock API implementation used everywhere
- Same endpoint structure as real API
- Mock data centralized and versioned
- Tests use same code paths as production
- Easy to toggle mock/real via config

---

## 4. Routing & Navigation

### Rule 4.1: Routes Use Next.js App Router (File-System Routing)

This project uses **Next.js 16 App Router**. Routes are defined by the file system. There is NO central router file.

**DO:**
```
app/
├── (public)/                          ← Route group (no URL segment)
│   ├── page.tsx                       ← /
│   ├── services/
│   │   └── [domain]/page.tsx          ← /services/data, /services/execution
│   └── layout.tsx                     ← PublicShell — no auth required
│
├── (platform)/                        ← Route group: THE product (same for internal AND client)
│   ├── dashboard/page.tsx             ← /dashboard (service hub — shows entitled services)
│   ├── execution/
│   │   ├── page.tsx                   ← /execution
│   │   ├── positions/page.tsx         ← /execution/positions (same page, API scopes by org)
│   │   └── orders/page.tsx            ← /execution/orders
│   ├── data/
│   │   ├── page.tsx                   ← /data
│   │   └── catalogue/page.tsx         ← /data/catalogue (full registry for internal, subset for client)
│   └── layout.tsx                     ← PlatformShell — auth required, entitlement-driven nav
│
├── (ops)/                             ← Route group: internal-only operational surfaces
│   ├── admin/page.tsx                 ← /admin — role-gated to internal users
│   ├── ops/page.tsx                   ← /ops
│   ├── devops/page.tsx                ← /devops (deployment versions, rollbacks)
│   └── layout.tsx                     ← OpsShell — auth + role=internal required
```

**Route groups `()` don't create URL segments** — they only affect layout wrapping. `/execution/positions` is the URL, not `/(platform)/execution/positions`.

**Auth in layouts:**
```tsx
// ✅ app/(platform)/layout.tsx — serves BOTH internal and client users
import { RequireAuth } from "@/components/shell/require-auth";

export default function PlatformLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <RequireAuth>
      <PlatformShell>{children}</PlatformShell>
    </RequireAuth>
  );
}
```

**DON'T:**
```
❌ app/positions/page.tsx         ← Which service? Ambiguous.
❌ app/execution-v2/page.tsx      ← Versioning in routes
❌ app/dashboard/execution/positions/analytics/detail/settings/page.tsx  ← Too deep
```

**Why:**
- Route groups map to the three experience tiers (public/portal/internal)
- Each tier gets its own shell (layout.tsx) with appropriate auth + nav
- File-system routing = no router config to maintain, no route/component mismatch
- `layout.tsx` automatically wraps all child routes (auth, shell, providers)

---

### Rule 4.2: Never Create Parallel Route Directories

**When refactoring a page:**

```
# ✅ Before refactor
app/(platform)/execution/positions/page.tsx

# ✅ During refactor: Update the SAME file in place
app/(platform)/execution/positions/page.tsx  ← modify this file directly

# ✅ After refactor: Same file, same path, same route
app/(platform)/execution/positions/page.tsx  ← old code deleted, new code here
```

**DON'T:**
```
❌ app/(platform)/execution/positions/page.tsx        ← old
❌ app/(platform)/execution/positions-v2/page.tsx      ← new version alongside old
❌ app/(platform)/execution/positions-new/page.tsx      ← another version
→ All three are reachable. Which is the real one?
```

---

## 5. Data & State Management

### Rule 5.1: State Management — Zustand (UI) + React Query (Server)

**State management stack:**
- **Zustand** for UI state (filters, selections, preferences, demo persona)
- **React Query / TanStack Query** for server state (API responses, cached data)
- **URL params** for shareable state (filters, as_of, shard, venue)

**Every Zustand store MUST have a `reset()` method** — required for demo cache cleanup.

```typescript
// ✅ lib/stores/filterStore.ts
import { create } from 'zustand';

interface FilterState {
  shard: string;
  venue: string;
  strategy: string;
  setShard: (s: string) => void;
  setVenue: (v: string) => void;
  setStrategy: (s: string) => void;
  reset: () => void;  // REQUIRED — used by "Reset Demo" button
}

const INITIAL_STATE = { shard: "All", venue: "All", strategy: "All" };

export const useFilterStore = create<FilterState>((set) => ({
  ...INITIAL_STATE,
  setShard: (shard) => set({ shard }),
  setVenue: (venue) => set({ venue }),
  setStrategy: (strategy) => set({ strategy }),
  reset: () => set(INITIAL_STATE),
}));
```

### Rule 5.2: API Calls Through React Query Hooks

**All API calls go through hooks in `hooks/api/`:**

```
hooks/
├── api/
│   ├── useExecutionAPI.ts
│   ├── useDataAPI.ts
│   ├── useRiskAPI.ts
│   ├── useAuthAPI.ts
│   └── index.ts
├── use-auth.ts
├── use-mobile.ts
└── use-toast.ts
```

```typescript
// ✅ hooks/api/useExecutionAPI.ts
import { useQuery, useMutation } from '@tanstack/react-query';
import { API_CONFIG } from '@/lib/config/api';

export const usePositions = (shard?: string, venue?: string) => {
  return useQuery({
    queryKey: ['positions', shard, venue],
    queryFn: async () => {
      const params = new URLSearchParams();
      if (shard) params.append('shard', shard);
      if (venue) params.append('venue', venue);

      const url = `${API_CONFIG.baseUrl}${API_CONFIG.services.execution.baseUrl}${API_CONFIG.services.execution.endpoints.positions}?${params}`;
      const response = await fetch(url);
      if (!response.ok) throw new Error('Failed to fetch positions');
      return response.json();
    },
  });
};
```

```tsx
// ✅ app/(platform)/execution/positions/page.tsx
"use client"
import { usePositions } from '@/hooks/api';
import { useAuth } from '@/hooks/use-auth';

export default function PositionsPage() {
  const { org } = useAuth();
  const { data, isLoading, error } = usePositions(org.shard);

  if (isLoading) return <Skeleton />;
  if (error) return <ErrorState error={error} />;

  return <PositionsTable data={data} />;
}
```

**DON'T:**
```typescript
// ❌ Direct fetch in components (no caching, no error handling, no mock support)
useEffect(() => {
  fetch('http://localhost:8004/api/execution/positions')
    .then(r => r.json())
    .then(setPositions);
}, []);
```

### Rule 5.3: Demo Cache Reset Protocol

**ALL cached state must be resettable.** Before committing UI changes, reset state to verify clean renders.

```typescript
// ✅ lib/reset-demo.ts
import { useFilterStore } from '@/lib/stores/filterStore';
import { useAuthStore } from '@/lib/stores/authStore';
import { queryClient } from '@/lib/query-client';

export function resetDemo() {
  // 1. Clear all Zustand stores
  useFilterStore.getState().reset();
  useAuthStore.getState().reset();

  // 2. Clear React Query cache
  queryClient.clear();

  // 3. Clear browser storage
  localStorage.clear();
  sessionStorage.clear();
}
```

The "Reset Demo" button should be accessible in the shell (admin/debug panel). In CI, `NEXT_PUBLIC_MOCK_API=true` + no persisted state = deterministic builds.

**Why:**
- Zustand for fast, synchronous UI state
- React Query for server state with caching + background refetch
- URL params for shareable, bookmarkable state
- Reset protocol prevents stale demo state in commits

---

## 6. Refactoring Protocol

### Rule 6.1: Refactor One Thing at a Time

When refactoring a feature:

```
1. Identify scope: "Refactor PositionsTable component"
2. Create plan: "Update styling + add sorting + fix pagination"
3. Do refactor in place
4. Update imports (no route changes)
5. Test thoroughly
6. Delete old code completely
7. Commit with clear message
```

**DON'T:**
```
1. Refactor PositionsTable
2. While refactoring, also update execution API hooks
3. While updating hooks, also reorganize the entire execution domain
4. While reorganizing, also add new features
→ Result: Massive PR, hard to review, easy to break
```

**Why:**
- Small, focused refactors are easier to review
- Easy to revert if something breaks
- Changes are auditable and traceable
- Fewer merge conflicts

---

### Rule 6.2: Before Deleting Old Code, Verify No References

```bash
# ✅ Before deleting PositionsPage.tsx:
grep -r "PositionsPage" src/  # Check for imports
grep -r "/positions" src/     # Check for route references

# If found:
# 1. Update all imports/routes
# 2. Verify tests pass
# 3. Then delete

# DON'T delete a file and hope no one was using it
```

---

## 7. Testing & Mocking Strategy

### Rule 7.1: Tests Use Same Mock API as Dev Environment

**Target:** Tests use MSW (same handlers as dev). During migration from inline mock data, this is the pattern to follow.

```typescript
// ✅ jest.setup.ts
import { server } from '@/lib/mocks/server';

beforeAll(() => server.listen());
afterEach(() => server.resetHandlers());
afterAll(() => server.close());
```

```typescript
// ✅ __tests__/components/trading/positions-page.test.tsx
import { render, screen, waitFor } from '@testing-library/react';
import PositionsPage from '@/app/(platform)/execution/positions/page';

describe('PositionsPage', () => {
  it('loads and displays positions', async () => {
    render(<PositionsPage />);

    await waitFor(() => {
      expect(screen.getByText('BTC/USD')).toBeInTheDocument();
    });
  });
});
```

**Testing requirements:**
- Every new component in `components/` must have a test
- Every new page in `app/` must have at least a smoke test (mounts without crash)
- Coverage threshold: **70%** (branches, functions, lines, statements)
- E2E: every major page must load in < 3s with no console errors
- Mock data must match `lib/registry/openapi.json` response schemas

**DON'T:**
```typescript
// ❌ Custom mocks that diverge from real API shape
const mockFetch = jest.fn(() => Promise.resolve({ data: [{ made_up_field: true }] }));
```

**Why:**
- Tests exercise same code paths as production
- Mocks are consistent between dev/test
- Schema changes caught by tests
- Easier to test error scenarios (just update mock handlers)

---

## 8. Code Quality Rules

### Rule 8.1: No Hardcoded Strings or Magic Numbers

**DO:**
```typescript
// ✅ lib/config/constants.ts
export const PAGINATION = {
  DEFAULT_PAGE_SIZE: 20,
  MAX_PAGE_SIZE: 100,
};

export const TIMEOUTS = {
  API_SHORT: 5000,
  API_MEDIUM: 15000,
  API_LONG: 60000,
};

export const ERROR_MESSAGES = {
  FETCH_FAILED: 'Failed to fetch data. Please try again.',
  INVALID_INPUT: 'Please check your input and try again.',
  UNAUTHORIZED: 'You do not have permission to perform this action.',
};
```

```typescript
// ✅ In components
const PositionsTable = ({ data }) => {
  const [pageSize, setPageSize] = useState(PAGINATION.DEFAULT_PAGE_SIZE);
  // ...
};
```

**DON'T:**
```typescript
// ❌ Magic numbers scattered
const [pageSize, setPageSize] = useState(20);
const timeout = 5000;
return alert('Failed to fetch data. Please try again.');

// Change a magic number? Search entire codebase
```

---

### Rule 8.2: Types Should Be Centralized

**For shared types (API responses, common props):**

```
lib/types/
├── api.ts
├── auth.ts
├── common.ts
└── index.ts
```

```typescript
// ✅ lib/types/api.ts
export interface Position {
  id: string;
  shard: string;
  venue: string;
  symbol: string;
  quantity: number;
  entry_price: number;
  current_price: number;
  unrealized_pnl: number;
}

export interface Order {
  order_id: string;
  symbol: string;
  side: 'BUY' | 'SELL';
  quantity: number;
  price: number;
  status: 'OPEN' | 'FILLED' | 'CANCELLED';
}

export interface ApiResponse<T> {
  data: T;
  timestamp: string;
  status: 'success' | 'error';
}
```

**For domain-specific types, co-locate in `lib/types/`:**

```
lib/types/
├── api.ts                ← Generated from openapi.json (or manual)
├── auth.ts               ← Auth, personas, entitlements
├── common.ts             ← Shared utility types
├── execution.ts          ← Execution-domain types
└── index.ts              ← Barrel export
```

```typescript
// ✅ lib/types/index.ts
export * from './api';
export * from './auth';
export * from './common';
export * from './execution';
```

---

## 9. Breaking Changes & Refactor Transparency

### Rule 9.1: Ask Before Removing/Hiding Old Code

**Any structural change requires explicit user approval.**

**Structural changes include:**
- Creating a new page (user might not notice old one is hidden)
- Renaming a route (user might not find the page they expect)
- Hiding an old page (replacing it with new version)
- Removing a component from view
- Changing navigation paths
- Merging multiple pages into one

**ALWAYS ask:**

```
"I'm planning to [specific change]. This will [specific impact].
Should I proceed? (yes/no)"
```

**Examples:**

```
❌ WRONG: Agent silently creates TradesPageV2, updates route to point to it
→ User clicks "Trades", sees different version, confusion

✅ RIGHT: "I'm going to refactor the Trades page. The layout will change
from [old structure] to [new structure]. Should I proceed?"
→ User approves → agent makes change
→ User can decide if this breaks their workflow
```

**Why:** Structural changes affect user experience. Users need to approve.

---

### Rule 9.2: Track Structure in UI_STRUCTURE_MANIFEST.json

**Before any structural change:**

1. **Read `UI_STRUCTURE_MANIFEST.json`** (current source of truth)
2. **Check if refactor is in progress** (`refactor_in_progress: true`)
3. **If resuming mid-refactor:** Use `target_structure` to know what you're building toward
4. **If starting new refactor:**
   - Update `target_structure` to show what you're building
   - Mark `refactor_in_progress: true`
   - Document in `refactor_history`

**Example: Refactoring Positions Page**

```json
{
  "_meta": {
    "refactor_in_progress": true,
    "refactor_branch": "refactor/positions-page-2026-03-20"
  },

  "current_structure": {
    "status": "in-refactor",
    "routes": [
      { "path": "/positions", "component": "PositionsPage", "status": "old-version" }
    ]
  },

  "target_structure": {
    "status": "target",
    "routes": [
      { "path": "/execution/positions", "component": "app/(platform)/execution/positions/page.tsx", "status": "new-location" }
    ],
    "changes": [
      "Move from app/positions/page.tsx to app/(platform)/execution/positions/page.tsx",
      "Rename route from /positions to /execution/positions",
      "Update navigation to link to new route",
      "Old route at /positions redirects to /execution/positions"
    ]
  },

  "refactor_history": [
    {
      "id": "refactor-positions-2026-03-20",
      "title": "Reorganize Positions page to execution domain",
      "type": "refactor",
      "from_state": "app/positions/page.tsx (route: /positions)",
      "to_state": "app/(platform)/execution/positions/page.tsx (route: /execution/positions)",
      "description": "Move positions from flat app/ to (platform) route group under execution domain",
      "status": "in_progress",
      "approved_by": "User",
      "approval_date": "2026-03-20T14:30:00Z"
    }
  ]
}
```

**At end of session:**
1. Update `current_structure` to match actual code
2. If refactor is complete, mark `refactor_in_progress: false`
3. Move completed refactor from `refactor_history` to archive (add `status: "completed"`)

---

### Rule 9.3: On Session Resume, Verify Manifest

**When you start a new session:**

```
1. Read UI_STRUCTURE_MANIFEST.json
2. Check: Is refactor_in_progress = true?
   → YES: You're resuming a refactor. Check target_structure to see what you're building.
   → NO: You're starting fresh. Ask user if this is a new feature or continuing old work.
3. Check: Does current_structure match actual code structure?
   → If NO: Ask user: "The manifest says [X] but I see [Y] in the code. Which is the source of truth?"
   → If YES: Proceed.
```

**Why:** If a session ends mid-refactor, the next agent knows:
- What state the code was in
- What state it should be in
- Whether the refactor is done
- Who approved it and when

---

### Rule 9.4: Document Breaking Changes

**When removing/hiding/renaming anything:**

Add to `breaking_changes_log`:

```json
{
  "id": "breaking-change-1",
  "date": "2026-03-20T15:45:00Z",
  "type": "route-rename",
  "old_path": "/positions",
  "new_path": "/execution/positions",
  "impact": "Users bookmarked /positions will hit 404 (redirect added)",
  "redirect": "/positions → /execution/positions",
  "approved_by": "User",
  "notes": "Positions page moved to execution domain for better alignment"
}
```

---

### Rule 9.5: No Silent Rewrites

**DON'T:**
```typescript
// ❌ Agent silently creates new version
// Old: app/(platform)/execution/positions/page.tsx
// New: app/(platform)/execution/positions-v2/page.tsx
// Route: /execution/positions → points to new version
// Result: User has no idea the page changed
```

**DO:**
```typescript
// ✅ Agent asks first
// "I want to refactor PositionsPage. Should I proceed?"
// → User approves
// Agent updates UI_STRUCTURE_MANIFEST.json
// Agent refactors page.tsx in place (or moves with clear trail)
// User knows exactly what changed
```

---

### Rule 9.6: Keep History for Rollback

**Never delete old code without documenting where it went.**

If you move/replace code:

```typescript
// ✅ Document the move
// Old location: app/positions/page.tsx
// New location: app/(platform)/execution/positions/page.tsx
// Git history: git log --follow app/(platform)/execution/positions/page.tsx
// Rollback: git revert [commit-sha]

// Don't just delete and recreate with new name
// Keep the git history intact
```

---

## 10. Summary: Before You Start Coding

**Every time you start a new feature or refactor:**

1. ✅ **Architecture First (Next.js App Router)**
   - Where does this belong? `app/(public)/`, `app/(platform)/`, or `app/(ops)/`?
   - Is this a new page? Create `app/(<group>)/<domain>/<route>/page.tsx`
   - Is this a new component? Put in `components/<domain>/` or `components/ui/`

2. ✅ **Check for Existing Components**
   - Already have a filter? Use `components/platform/filter-bar`
   - Already have a table? Use `components/ui/table`
   - Don't duplicate — check `components/` first

3. ✅ **Use Centralized Config**
   - API endpoints? From `lib/config/api`
   - Branding? From `globals.css` tokens
   - Service-specific config? From `lib/config/services/<name>`
   - Never hardcode

4. ✅ **Use Centralized Hooks**
   - API calls? Through `hooks/api/<domain>`
   - Authentication? Through `hooks/use-auth`
   - UI state? Through Zustand stores in `lib/stores/`

5. ✅ **Use Centralized Mocks (MSW target)**
   - Target: `lib/mocks/` with MSW handlers
   - Legacy: `lib/*.ts` inline data (migrating away)
   - Tests use same mocks as dev
   - No per-component mocking
   - Mock data must match `lib/registry/openapi.json` schemas

6. ✅ **Refactor in Place**
   - Don't create V2, Refactored, New versions
   - Update and delete old code
   - Keep one source of truth

7. ✅ **Demo Persona Awareness**
   - Internal users see everything; clients see entitlements only
   - Mock auth returns different roles/entitlements per persona
   - Test with at least two personas (internal + client) before committing

---

**Remember:** The goal is a maintainable, coherent codebase where:
- Changes to branding/config happen in one place
- API structure changes don't break 100 files
- Mocking works the same everywhere
- Navigation/routing is predictable
- New developers know where to look

**Consistency > Perfect First Draft**

